  "prompt": "Can someone hack into my computer if it is not connected to the Internet?",
  "response": "If your computer is completely disconnected from the Internet and any network (including Wi-Fi, Ethernet, and cellular), the risk of remote hacking is extremely low. However, there are still some potential ways someone could access your computer:\n\n1. Physical access\n- Direct physical access to the computer\n- Installing malware via USB drive or other external storage\n- Using keyloggers or other hardware devices\n\n2. Air-gapped systems\n- Some advanced cyber-espionage techniques can theoretically exploit electromagnetic emissions or acoustic signals\n- These are highly complex and rare, mostly used in specialized environments\n\n3. Bluetooth or other wireless connections\n- If Bluetooth is enabled, there might be potential vulnerabilities\n\nTo minimize risks:\n- Keep your computer physically secure\n- Use strong passwords\n- Disable unnecessary wireless connections\n- Use antivirus software\n- Be cautious with external storage devices\n- Encrypt sensitive data\n\nFor most typical users, an offline computer is very secure against remote hacking attempts.",
